isplay: block;\"\n    ></span>\n    <picture>\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/2263d/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.webp 200w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/e1fb3/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.webp 400w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/9e719/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.webp 800w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/5d9b9/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.webp 900w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/webp\"\n        />\n        <source\n          srcset=\"/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/23638/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg 200w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/f5e05/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg 400w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/2fa10/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg 800w,\n/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/ea3b0/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg 900w\"\n          sizes=\"(max-width: 800px) 100vw, 800px\"\n          type=\"image/jpeg\"\n        />\n        <img\n          class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n          style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;box-shadow:inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n          src=\"/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/2fa10/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg\"\n          alt=\"Planning\"\n          title=\"Planning\"\n        />\n      </picture>\n  </span></p>\n<h2>Ng new</h2>\n<p>Yes, it's the Angular cli's <code class=\"language-jstext\">ng new</code>. It offers a couple of options to configure when starting a new project. For example, style-sheet type <code class=\"language-jstext\">css | scss</code> or app <code class=\"language-jstext\">prefix</code> or application's <code class=\"language-jstext\">routing</code>. I find it is much easier to configure at the beginning of the project than later skimming through <code class=\"language-jstext\">angular.json</code>.</p>\n<h2>Setting up code linter</h2>\n<p>Angular comes bundle with ready to use <code class=\"language-jstext\">tslint</code>, which proves to be the Typescript's best friend. Reading through <a href=\"https://palantir.github.io/tslint/rules/\">here</a> you will find a list of tslint's configuration options, tinker them to suit your team's standard.\nFurthermore, <code class=\"language-jstext\">stylelint</code> can also be apply at them same way.</p>\n<h2>Setting up code formatter</h2>\n<p>Different team members may use a different code formatter in their IDE or text editor, a package name <code class=\"language-jstext\">prettier</code> can be use to consistently format the code according to the configured options in <code class=\"language-jstext\">.prettierrc.json</code> file.</p>\n<h2>Setting up git hook</h2>\n<p>To enforce linter's rules and prevent bad code from committing to repository, package like husky can be used to intercept git hooks. I always pair them up with lint-staged to only run linters and format code on staged files.</p>\n<h2>Decide modules structure</h2>\n<p>I always go with typical core/shared/feature modules option when the project is small to medium scale. It's far more than enough for most of the use cases. Then finally, think about your application business requirement and decide modules/routings accordingly. Always try to decide a reusable components and always <strong>DRY</strong> <em>(don't repeat yourself)</em> and <strong>KISS</strong> <em>(keep it simple stupid)</em>.</p>\n<h2>Code style</h2>\n<p>Setup team's code style. I usually refers to the official <a href=\"https://angular.io/guide/styleguide\">Angular's style guide</a>, but there are plenty of things that aren't mentioned like Observable should end with <code class=\"language-jstext\">$</code>. Brainstorm and create a short team's style guide in wiki, so that they can be shared between the team members or even throughout the organization.</p>\n<p>Remember that these are meant to improve code quality and long-term productivity. If it doesn't for your team, don't bother doing it.</p>","excerpt":"Ng newYes, it's the Angular cli's . It offers a couple of options to configure when starting a new project. For example, style-sheet type  or app  or application's . I find it is much easier to configure at the beginning of the project than later skimming through .Setting up code linterAngular comes…","frontmatter":{"title":"Setting up a new Angular project","description":"My personal notes when setting up a new small to medium scale Angular project","date":"13 June, 2019","thumbnail":{"childImageSharp":{"resize":{"src":"/blog/static/92e9a37e56e13e397e6d32c26b0d2ef6/48ccc/jeff-sheldon-3220-unsplash.jpg"}}}}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/setting-up-new-angular-project/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/automate-project-versioning-changelog/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Automate versioning & CHANGELOG"}},"next":{"fields":{"slug":"/sass-partials/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"SASS partials"}}}}}